Index templates define the settings, mappings, and aliases that are automatically applied when a new index matching a pattern is created.

Composable index templates

Modern Elasticsearch uses composable index templates (sometimes called index templates v2). They consist of a top-level template and optional component templates.

Create a composable index template:
  PUT /_index_template/my-logs-template
  {
    "index_patterns": ["logs-*"],
    "template": {
      "settings": {
        "number_of_shards": 1,
        "number_of_replicas": 1,
        "index.lifecycle.name": "logs-ilm-policy"
      },
      "mappings": {
        "properties": {
          "@timestamp": { "type": "date" },
          "message": { "type": "text" },
          "level": { "type": "keyword" }
        }
      }
    },
    "priority": 200
  }

Component templates

Component templates are reusable building blocks for settings and mappings:
  PUT /_component_template/common-mappings
  {
    "template": {
      "mappings": {
        "properties": {
          "@timestamp": { "type": "date" },
          "host.name": { "type": "keyword" }
        }
      }
    }
  }

Reference component templates from a composable template:
  PUT /_index_template/my-template
  {
    "index_patterns": ["metrics-*"],
    "composed_of": ["common-mappings", "my-settings"],
    "template": { ... }
  }

Data stream templates

To use a template for data streams, set data_stream: {}:
  PUT /_index_template/logs-data-stream-template
  {
    "index_patterns": ["logs-*-*"],
    "data_stream": {},
    "template": { ... }
  }

Template priority

When multiple templates match an index name, the one with the highest priority wins. Built-in Elastic templates use priority 100. Set custom templates to 200 or higher to override them.

Transforms pivot or summarize data from source indices into destination indices. They are useful for creating aggregated views, entity-centric summaries, and derived datasets.

Transform types

Pivot transform: Aggregates data like a SQL GROUP BY. Groups documents by one or more grouping fields and applies aggregations (sum, avg, terms, etc.) to compute summary values.

Latest transform: Creates entity-centric documents from the most recent values for each entity. Useful for creating a current-state view from time-series data (e.g., latest telemetry per host).

Continuous vs. batch transforms

Batch transform: Runs once and completes.

Continuous transform: Runs incrementally, updating the destination index as new source data arrives. Use sync.time.field and sync.time.delay to configure the synchronization field and delay.

Creating a pivot transform

  PUT /_transform/sales-by-category
  {
    "source": { "index": "sales" },
    "dest": { "index": "sales-summary" },
    "pivot": {
      "group_by": {
        "category": { "terms": { "field": "category.keyword" } }
      },
      "aggregations": {
        "total_revenue": { "sum": { "field": "revenue" } },
        "avg_order": { "avg": { "field": "order_total" } }
      }
    },
    "frequency": "5m"
  }

Transform node role

Transforms require at least one node with the transform role. Without a transform node, transforms cannot run.

Managing transforms

  POST /_transform/sales-by-category/_start
  POST /_transform/sales-by-category/_stop
  GET /_transform/sales-by-category/_stats

Watcher is Elasticsearch's built-in alerting and notification system. Watches monitor conditions in your data and trigger actions when thresholds are met.

Watch anatomy

A watch consists of:
1. Trigger: When the watch runs (typically a schedule).
2. Input: What data to load (search results, HTTP response, etc.).
3. Condition: Logic to evaluate the input and decide whether to act.
4. Actions: What to do when the condition is true (email, webhook, index, Slack, etc.).

Example watch

  PUT /_watcher/watch/cluster-health-check
  {
    "trigger": { "schedule": { "interval": "5m" } },
    "input": {
      "http": {
        "request": {
          "host": "localhost",
          "port": 9200,
          "path": "/_cluster/health"
        }
      }
    },
    "condition": {
      "compare": {
        "ctx.payload.status": { "eq": "red" }
      }
    },
    "actions": {
      "notify_slack": {
        "webhook": {
          "method": "POST",
          "url": "https://hooks.slack.com/...",
          "body": "{\"text\": \"Cluster health is RED!\"}"
        }
      }
    }
  }

Watcher vs. Kibana Alerting

Kibana Alerting (Rules and Connectors) is the modern alerting system with a UI, more rule types, and broader action support. Watcher remains available for backwards compatibility and for users who prefer the Elasticsearch API for alert management.

Monitoring Watcher

Check watch execution history:
  GET /_watcher/watch/cluster-health-check/_status
  GET /_watcher/stats

The reindex API copies documents from a source index to a destination index. Use it when you need to change mappings, settings, or restructure data.

Basic reindex

  POST /_reindex
  {
    "source": { "index": "old-index" },
    "dest": { "index": "new-index" }
  }

The destination index is created automatically with dynamic mapping if it doesn't exist. To use custom mappings, create the destination index first.

Filtered reindex

Reindex a subset of documents:
  POST /_reindex
  {
    "source": {
      "index": "old-index",
      "query": { "range": { "@timestamp": { "gte": "now-30d" } } }
    },
    "dest": { "index": "new-index" }
  }

Reindex with script

Transform documents during reindex:
  POST /_reindex
  {
    "source": { "index": "old-index" },
    "dest": { "index": "new-index" },
    "script": {
      "source": "ctx._source.new_field = ctx._source.old_field; ctx._source.remove('old_field')"
    }
  }

Remote reindex

Reindex from a remote Elasticsearch cluster:
  POST /_reindex
  {
    "source": {
      "remote": {
        "host": "https://remote-cluster:9200",
        "username": "user",
        "password": "..."
      },
      "index": "source-index"
    },
    "dest": { "index": "dest-index" }
  }

Async reindex

For large indices, run reindex asynchronously:
  POST /_reindex?wait_for_completion=false

This returns a task ID. Monitor progress:
  GET /_tasks/<task-id>

Performance tips

- Set refresh_interval: -1 on the destination index during reindex, then restore to 1s.
- Increase number_of_replicas to 0 during reindex, restore after.
- Use the requests_per_second parameter to throttle reindex to avoid impacting production.

Dense vector embeddings consume significant memory. This page covers strategies for reducing memory usage while maintaining acceptable search recall.

Memory usage of dense vectors

A 768-dimensional float32 vector requires 768 * 4 bytes = 3 KB. For a corpus of 10 million documents, that is 30 GB of memory — before accounting for the HNSW graph overhead.

HNSW graph memory

In addition to raw vector storage, the HNSW index graph requires additional memory proportional to the m parameter. Higher m = more memory but better recall.

Quantization strategies

Quantization reduces the per-vector memory footprint:

int8 (scalar quantization):
  "index_options": { "type": "int8_hnsw" }
~75% memory reduction. Recall impact minimal (typically >95% of full precision recall).

int4:
  "index_options": { "type": "int4_hnsw" }
~87% memory reduction. Moderate recall impact.

BBQ (Binary Bit Quantization):
  "index_options": { "type": "bbq_hnsw" }
~96% memory reduction (32x compression). Recall impact is significant — suitable for very large corpora where memory is the primary constraint, combined with oversampling (num_candidates much higher than k).

exclude_source_vectors

In 9.2+, exclude_source_vectors: true (default) removes vector values from _source. This saves additional storage — vectors are retained in the HNSW index but not in the stored field.

Rescoring with quantized indices

For BBQ and int4 quantization, use oversampling and rescoring to recover recall:
  {
    "knn": {
      "field": "body_vector",
      "query_vector": [...],
      "k": 10,
      "num_candidates": 1000
    },
    "rescore": {
      "window_size": 100,
      "query": {
        "rescore_query": {
          "script_score": {
            "query": { "match_all": {} },
            "script": { "source": "cosineSimilarity(params.vec, 'body_vector') + 1.0", "params": { "vec": [...] } }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

Benchmark before choosing quantization. The right choice depends on your corpus size, memory budget, and acceptable recall threshold.

Relevance tuning involves adjusting how Elasticsearch scores and ranks documents to return the most useful results for your users.

Understanding BM25 scoring

Elasticsearch uses BM25 as the default similarity algorithm. BM25 scores are based on:
1. Term frequency (TF): How often the query term appears in the document.
2. Inverse document frequency (IDF): How rare the term is across the corpus.
3. Field length normalization: Documents with shorter fields score higher for the same term frequency.

BM25 rewards exact vocabulary overlap. It cannot bridge synonyms, paraphrases, or semantic relationships without explicit synonym configuration.

Explain API

The explain API shows why a document received a particular score:
  GET /my-index/_explain/doc-001
  {
    "query": { "match": { "body": "authentication failure" } }
  }

The response breaks down the score computation: which terms matched, their TF and IDF contributions, and the field length normalization factor.

Boosting

Boost specific fields or clauses to increase their contribution to the score:
  {
    "multi_match": {
      "query": "elasticsearch cluster",
      "fields": ["title^3", "body"]
    }
  }

title is boosted 3x — matches in the title count more than matches in the body.

Synonym configuration

Add a synonym token filter to the analyzer to expand queries with related terms:
  "filter": {
    "my_synonyms": {
      "type": "synonym",
      "synonyms": ["login, sign in, authentication", "error, failure, exception"]
    }
  }

With synonyms, a search for 'login failure' can match documents containing 'authentication error'. Without synonyms, BM25 would return zero results for a vocabulary mismatch.

Vector search as a relevance complement

Vector search does not require exact vocabulary overlap. A kNN search for an embedding of 'user can\'t log in' will retrieve documents about 'authentication failure' because the embedding space captures semantic similarity. Hybrid search (BM25 + kNN via RRF) combines both signals for improved relevance.

The dense_vector field type stores dense float vectors for use in kNN (k-nearest neighbor) search and vector similarity scoring.

Basic mapping

  {
    "mappings": {
      "properties": {
        "my_vector": {
          "type": "dense_vector",
          "dims": 768,
          "index": true,
          "similarity": "cosine"
        }
      }
    }
  }

dims: The number of dimensions in the vector. Required. Vectors of a different dimension cannot be indexed in this field.

index: When true, the field supports approximate kNN search. When false, only exact search is available. Defaults to true.

Similarity metrics

similarity controls how vector distance is calculated:
- cosine: Cosine similarity (normalized dot product). Good for text embeddings where vector magnitude is not meaningful.
- dot_product: Raw dot product. Requires unit-length (normalized) vectors.
- l2_norm: Euclidean distance. Smaller distance = higher score.
- max_inner_product: Maximizes dot product. Does not require normalization.

HNSW index options

The Hierarchical Navigable Small World (HNSW) algorithm is used for approximate kNN indexing.

  "index_options": {
    "type": "hnsw",
    "m": 16,
    "ef_construction": 100
  }

m: Controls the number of neighbors tracked for each node in the HNSW graph. Higher values improve recall at the cost of more memory and slower indexing. Default: 16.
ef_construction: Controls the number of candidates examined during indexing. Higher values improve recall and index quality but slow indexing. Default: 100.

Quantization

Vector quantization reduces memory usage by storing vectors at lower precision.

int8 quantization (scalar quantization):
  "index_options": {
    "type": "int8_hnsw",
    "confidence_interval": 0.9
  }
Reduces memory by ~75% with minimal recall loss.

int4 quantization:
  "index_options": {
    "type": "int4_hnsw"
  }
More aggressive quantization — ~87% memory reduction with greater recall impact.

BBQ (Binary Bit Quantization):
  "index_options": {
    "type": "bbq_hnsw"
  }
Extreme quantization — reduces each float to a single bit. 32x memory reduction. Recall is lower; recommended for very large corpora where memory is the constraint and some recall loss is acceptable.

Flat index (exact search)

  "index_options": {
    "type": "flat"
  }
Stores raw vectors without HNSW graph for exact (brute-force) search. Use when dataset is small or when perfect recall is required. No quantization available for flat index.

exclude_source_vectors

When true (default in 9.2+), vector values are excluded from the _source field. This reduces storage at the cost of not being able to retrieve vector values directly. The vector is still fully indexed for search.

kNN search example

  {
    "knn": {
      "field": "my_vector",
      "query_vector": [0.1, 0.2, ...],
      "k": 10,
      "num_candidates": 100
    }
  }

k: Number of nearest neighbors to return.
num_candidates: Number of candidates considered per shard before the final top-k merge. Higher values improve recall. Typically 5-10x k.

Vector similarity scoring in queries

Use script_score with cosineSimilarity, dotProduct, or l2norm functions to score documents by vector distance in a regular query context (non-approximate search).

The semantic_text field type enables semantic search by automatically generating and storing vector embeddings at index time using a configured inference endpoint.

Basic mapping

  {
    "mappings": {
      "properties": {
        "body": {
          "type": "semantic_text",
          "inference_id": ".elser-2-elasticsearch"
        }
      }
    }
  }

inference_id: The ID of the inference endpoint to use for generating embeddings. If omitted, the default inference endpoint is used. For production, always specify inference_id explicitly — the default endpoint can change across versions, causing mixed embedding models across indices and ranking issues in multi-index searches.

chunking_settings: Controls how long documents are split into chunks before embedding. Each chunk is embedded independently.

  "chunking_settings": {
    "strategy": "sentence",
    "max_chunk_size": 250,
    "sentence_overlap": 1
  }

Strategies: word (split on word count), sentence (split on sentence boundaries).

How semantic_text works

When a document is indexed with a semantic_text field:
1. The field content is sent to the configured inference endpoint.
2. The model generates embeddings (dense or sparse vectors depending on the model).
3. The embeddings are stored internally with the document.
4. At query time, the match query on a semantic_text field automatically embeds the query text and performs vector similarity search.

Querying semantic_text fields

Use the match query (which automatically detects semantic_text fields and triggers vector search):
  { "query": { "match": { "body": { "query": "what causes cluster health to go red" } } } }

Or use the semantic query type explicitly:
  { "query": { "semantic": { "field": "body", "query": "cluster health red" } } }

Pre-filtering

For hybrid search combining semantic_text with other fields, use the retriever framework with a filter clause to apply pre-filters before vector retrieval:
  {
    "retriever": {
      "knn": {
        "field": "body",
        "query_vector_builder": { "text_embedding": { ... } },
        "filter": { "term": { "product": "elasticsearch" } }
      }
    }
  }

Limitations

- semantic_text is not supported on indices created before Elasticsearch 8.11.0.
- Cross-cluster replication (CCR) is not supported for indices containing semantic_text fields.
- The _source for semantic_text fields stores the original text but not the embedding vectors (by default).
- Updating the inference_id after index creation is not supported — you must reindex.

Hybrid search combines full-text search (BM25 lexical matching) with vector search (semantic/kNN search) to leverage the strengths of both approaches.

Why hybrid search?

Full-text (BM25) search excels at exact keyword matching — it rewards documents that contain the exact query terms. Vector search excels at semantic similarity — it finds documents that are conceptually related even when exact vocabulary differs. Hybrid search combines these signals to improve overall relevance.

Recommended approach: RRF (Reciprocal Rank Fusion)

Elasticsearch recommends using the rrf retriever for hybrid search. RRF merges ranked result lists from multiple retrievers without requiring score normalization:
  {
    "retriever": {
      "rrf": {
        "retrievers": [
          { "standard": { "query": { "match": { "title": "elasticsearch vector" } } } },
          { "knn": { "field": "title_vector", "query_vector": [...], "k": 5, "num_candidates": 50 } }
        ],
        "rank_constant": 60,
        "rank_window_size": 100
      }
    }
  }

RRF is robust to score scale differences between BM25 and vector search. The rank_constant (default 60) controls how much early ranks are boosted. The rank_window_size controls how many top results from each retriever are considered.

Alternative: Linear retriever

For cases where you need explicit score weighting, the linear retriever normalizes and linearly combines scores from multiple retrievers using configurable weights and normalizers (minmax, l2_norm).

When to use hybrid search

- Use BM25-only when exact terminology matching is paramount (e.g., searching code, configuration keys, error messages).
- Use vector-only when semantic understanding is paramount and vocabulary varies widely.
- Use hybrid when both vocabulary and semantics matter — the typical case for documentation search, customer support, and general knowledge retrieval.

Retrievers provide a composable framework for building search pipelines. They replace and generalize the previous knn, query, and rescore parameters.

Retriever types

standard: Wraps a standard Elasticsearch query.
  { "standard": { "query": { "match": { "title": "search" } } } }

knn: Runs approximate kNN vector search.
  { "knn": { "field": "vector", "query_vector": [...], "k": 10, "num_candidates": 100 } }

rrf: Reciprocal Rank Fusion — combines ranked result lists from multiple sub-retrievers. Recommended for hybrid search.
  {
    "rrf": {
      "retrievers": [ <retriever1>, <retriever2> ],
      "rank_constant": 60,
      "rank_window_size": 100
    }
  }

linear: Normalizes and combines scores from sub-retrievers with configurable weights. Use when explicit score weighting is needed.
  {
    "linear": {
      "retrievers": [
        { "retriever": { "knn": {...} }, "weight": 5, "normalizer": "minmax" },
        { "retriever": { "standard": {...} }, "weight": 1.5 }
      ]
    }
  }

text_similarity_reranker: Re-ranks results from a sub-retriever using a text similarity cross-encoder model.
  {
    "text_similarity_reranker": {
      "retriever": { "rrf": {...} },
      "rank_window_size": 100,
      "inference_id": "my-reranker",
      "inference_text": "search query",
      "field": "body"
    }
  }

Multi-field query format

The linear retriever (9.1+) supports a multi-field query format that automatically groups fields by type:
- Semantic (semantic_text or dense_vector) fields receive vector search.
- Lexical (text, keyword) fields receive BM25 match.

This enables a single query string to search across both semantic and lexical fields with automatic field grouping:
  {
    "retriever": {
      "linear": {
        "query": "elasticsearch vector search",
        "fields": ["title", "body", "body_semantic"],
        "normalizer": "minmax"
      }
    }
  }

Composing retrievers

Retrievers are composable. You can use any retriever as a sub-retriever inside rrf, linear, or text_similarity_reranker. This enables complex pipelines such as: (kNN + BM25 via RRF) → reranker.

The linear retriever normalizes and linearly combines the scores of other retrievers using a weighted sum formula.

Score formula:
  Score = sum(weight_i * Normalizer(Score_i))

Parameters

retrievers: Array of sub-retriever configurations. Each entry specifies:
  - retriever: A retriever object (standard, knn, etc.)
  - weight: Multiplier applied after normalization. Default: 1.0. Must be >= 0.
  - normalizer: Per-retriever normalizer. Overrides the top-level normalizer.

rank_window_size: Size of the per-retriever result set before merging. Default: 10. Must be >= size.

normalizer (top-level): Default normalizer applied to all sub-retrievers that don't specify their own. Required when using the query parameter (multi-field query format).

query (9.1+): Query string for the multi-field query format. Automatically dispatches to semantic or lexical sub-retrievers based on field type.

fields (9.1+): Fields to query when using the multi-field format. Supports boost notation (field^2).

Normalizers

none: No normalization. Avoid when combining BM25 and kNN — score scales are incompatible and will bias results toward lexical matches.

minmax: Normalizes scores to [0,1] range:
  score = (score - min) / (max - min)

l2_norm (9.1+): Normalizes using the L2 norm of the score vector.

Example: Hybrid search with explicit weights

  {
    "retriever": {
      "linear": {
        "retrievers": [
          {
            "retriever": {
              "knn": {
                "field": "title_vector",
                "query_vector": [0.1, 0.2, 0.3],
                "k": 10,
                "num_candidates": 100
              }
            },
            "weight": 5
          },
          {
            "retriever": {
              "standard": {
                "query": { "match": { "title": "elasticsearch" } }
              }
            },
            "weight": 1.5
          }
        ],
        "normalizer": "minmax"
      }
    }
  }

In this example, kNN results are weighted 5x and BM25 results 1.5x after minmax normalization. This allows you to tune the relative importance of semantic vs. lexical signals based on your use case.

This tutorial walks you through setting up semantic search using the semantic_text field type. By the end, you will be able to create an index mapping with a semantic_text field, ingest documents that are automatically converted to vector embeddings, and query your data using semantic search.

The semantic_text field type simplifies the inference workflow by providing inference at ingestion time with sensible defaults. You don't need to define model-related settings, parameters, or create inference ingest pipelines.

Requirements

This tutorial uses the Elastic Inference Service (EIS), which is automatically enabled on Elastic Cloud Hosted deployments and Serverless projects. You can also use EIS for self-managed clusters by connecting to the service.

Create the index mapping

Create a destination index with a semantic_text field:
  PUT /semantic-embeddings
  {
    "mappings": {
      "properties": {
        "content": {
          "type": "semantic_text"
        }
      }
    }
  }

Since no inference_id is specified, the default inference endpoint is used. For production, explicitly specify inference_id to avoid ranking issues from mixed embedding models.

To use ML-nodes with ELSER instead of EIS:
  {
    "content": {
      "type": "semantic_text",
      "inference_id": ".elser-2-elasticsearch"
    }
  }

Ingest data

When you index a document, Elasticsearch automatically sends the semantic_text field content to the inference endpoint, generates embeddings, and stores them:
  POST /semantic-embeddings/_bulk
  { "index": { "_id": "1" } }
  { "content": "After running, cool down with light cardio to reduce muscle soreness." }
  { "index": { "_id": "2" } }
  { "content": "Tune cluster performance by monitoring thread pools and refresh interval." }

Run a semantic search query

Query DSL — the match query automatically detects the semantic_text field and runs semantic search:
  {
    "query": {
      "match": {
        "content": {
          "query": "What causes muscle soreness after running?"
        }
      }
    }
  }

ES|QL — use the match (:) operator with METADATA _score:
  FROM semantic-embeddings METADATA _score
  | WHERE content: "How to avoid muscle soreness while running?"
  | SORT _score DESC
  | LIMIT 1000

The match query returns documents ranked by semantic relevance. Documents about running and recovery will score highest even if the exact query words don't appear in the document.

An index lifecycle management (ILM) policy defines how indices transition through phases over time. This guide explains how to create a new ILM policy with configurable rollover, retention, and deletion rules, and then apply the policy using an index template.

Create a lifecycle policy

Use the Create or update policy API:
  PUT /_ilm/policy/my-policy
  {
    "policy": {
      "phases": {
        "hot": {
          "actions": {
            "rollover": {
              "max_primary_shard_size": "25GB"
            }
          }
        },
        "delete": {
          "min_age": "30d",
          "actions": {
            "delete": {}
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

This policy rolls over the index when a primary shard reaches 25 GB, then deletes the index 30 days after rollover.

Create an index template to apply the policy

Apply the policy via an index template using index.lifecycle.name:
  PUT /_index_template/my-template
  {
    "index_patterns": ["test-*"],
    "template": {
      "settings": {
        "number_of_shards": 1,
        "number_of_replicas": 1,
        "index.lifecycle.name": "my-policy",
        "index.lifecycle.rollover_alias": "test-alias"
      }
    }
  }

Note: index.lifecycle.rollover_alias is required only when using ILM with rolling indices and an alias. It is not needed when using data streams.

Create an initial managed index (rolling indices only)

For rolling indices, create the initial write index manually:
  PUT /test-000001
  {
    "aliases": {
      "test-alias": {
        "is_write_index": true
      }
    }
  }

Index naming must match the template pattern and end with a number so ILM can increment it on rollover.

ILM policy storage and snapshots

ILM policies are stored in global cluster state. When taking a snapshot with include_global_state: true, ILM policies are included. When the snapshot is restored, stored policies overwrite any local policies with the same name.

Ingest pipelines transform and enrich documents before indexing. A pipeline is a sequence of processors, each performing a specific operation on the document.

Creating a pipeline

Use the Create ingest pipeline API:
  PUT /_ingest/pipeline/my-pipeline
  {
    "description": "Extract and enrich log fields",
    "processors": [
      {
        "grok": {
          "field": "message",
          "patterns": ["%{IP:client_ip} %{WORD:method} %{URIPATHPARAM:request}"]
        }
      },
      {
        "date": {
          "field": "@timestamp",
          "formats": ["ISO8601"]
        }
      }
    ]
  }

Common processor types

- set: Sets a field value.
- rename: Renames a field.
- remove: Deletes a field.
- grok: Extracts structured fields from a string using grok patterns.
- date: Parses and formats date fields.
- convert: Converts a field type (string to integer, etc.).
- script: Runs an inline Painless script.
- enrich: Adds data from an enrich policy (joins with reference data).
- inference: Runs ML inference on a field using a deployed model.
- foreach: Iterates over array elements and applies a sub-processor.

Conditional processors

Add an if condition to run a processor only when a condition is true:
  {
    "set": {
      "if": "ctx.status_code == 404",
      "field": "event.outcome",
      "value": "not_found"
    }
  }

Failure handling

Each processor can have an on_failure block:
  {
    "grok": {
      "field": "message",
      "patterns": ["..."],
      "on_failure": [
        {
          "set": {
            "field": "error.message",
            "value": "Grok failed: {{ _ingest.on_failure_message }}"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  }

The pipeline-level on_failure block catches errors not handled by individual processor on_failure blocks.

Pipeline simulation

Test a pipeline before deploying:
  POST /_ingest/pipeline/my-pipeline/_simulate
  {
    "docs": [
      { "_source": { "message": "192.168.1.1 GET /api/search" } }
    ]
  }

Pipeline as default or final pipeline

Set index.default_pipeline to run a pipeline for all documents indexed to an index. Set index.final_pipeline to run after the default pipeline.

k-nearest neighbor (kNN) search finds the k vectors most similar to a query vector. It is the foundation of semantic search in Elasticsearch.

Exact vs. approximate kNN

Exact kNN (brute-force) calculates the distance from the query vector to every indexed vector. It guarantees perfect recall but is too slow for large datasets (O(n) per query).

Approximate kNN (ANN) uses the HNSW algorithm to find approximate nearest neighbors much faster, with a small, controllable trade-off in recall. For most production use cases, approximate kNN at index: true is the right choice.

Basic kNN search

  POST /my-index/_search
  {
    "knn": {
      "field": "my_vector",
      "query_vector": [0.3, 0.1, 1.2, ...],
      "k": 5,
      "num_candidates": 50
    }
  }

k: Number of nearest neighbors to return.
num_candidates: Number of approximate nearest neighbors collected per shard before the global top-k merge. Higher values improve recall. Typically set to 5-10x k.

Using a query vector builder

Instead of providing a pre-computed vector, generate the query vector at search time using an inference endpoint:
  {
    "knn": {
      "field": "body_vector",
      "query_vector_builder": {
        "text_embedding": {
          "model_id": ".multilingual-e5-small-elasticsearch",
          "model_text": "what causes cluster health to go red"
        }
      },
      "k": 10,
      "num_candidates": 100
    }
  }

Recall vs. latency trade-offs

Higher num_candidates = better recall, slower query. Lower num_candidates = faster query, lower recall. Benchmark your use case to find the right balance.

Higher HNSW m and ef_construction at index time = better recall and a more accurate graph, but slower indexing and more memory.

Filtered kNN

Apply pre-filters to narrow the search space:
  {
    "knn": {
      "field": "body_vector",
      "query_vector": [...],
      "k": 10,
      "num_candidates": 100,
      "filter": { "term": { "product": "elasticsearch" } }
    }
  }

Pre-filtering (applied before HNSW traversal) is more efficient than post-filtering (applied to results). Elasticsearch automatically applies kNN filters as pre-filters.

Multi-vector search

Multiple kNN clauses can be combined in a single search request, or combined with BM25 queries. The knn retriever in the retrievers framework is the recommended approach for combining vector and keyword search (hybrid search).

Aggregations summarize, group, and compute statistics over your data. They run alongside search queries and can be combined with filters.

Aggregation types

Bucket aggregations: Group documents into buckets based on field values, ranges, or other criteria.
- terms: Groups documents by field value (most common for faceting).
- range: Groups by numeric or date ranges.
- date_histogram: Groups time-series data by time interval (useful for charts).
- filter / filters: Single or multiple filter buckets.
- nested: Accesses nested object documents.

Metric aggregations: Compute statistics within buckets.
- avg: Average value.
- min / max: Minimum and maximum values.
- sum: Sum of values.
- cardinality: Approximate count of distinct values.
- stats: Returns count, min, max, avg, and sum together.
- percentiles: Approximate percentile values.

Pipeline aggregations: Operate on the output of other aggregations.
- moving_avg: Moving average over a series of bucket values.
- bucket_sort: Sorts buckets by sub-aggregation value.
- cumulative_sum: Cumulative running total across buckets.

Example: Terms aggregation

  {
    "aggs": {
      "products": {
        "terms": { "field": "product.keyword", "size": 10 }
      }
    }
  }

Nested aggregations

Aggregations can be nested inside bucket aggregations to compute sub-statistics:
  {
    "aggs": {
      "by_product": {
        "terms": { "field": "product.keyword" },
        "aggs": {
          "avg_score": { "avg": { "field": "score" } }
        }
      }
    }
  }

Performance notes

High-cardinality terms aggregations on text fields require fielddata (heap-intensive). Use keyword fields for aggregations. Set search.max_buckets to limit bucket counts and prevent memory exhaustion from deeply nested aggregations.

Painless is Elasticsearch's built-in scripting language. It is designed for safety and performance in the Elasticsearch execution environment.

Use cases

- Custom field computation in script_score queries.
- Ingest pipeline script processors.
- Runtime fields (compute field values at query time without storing them).
- Aggregation scripting.
- Update scripts (partial document updates with logic).

Basic Painless syntax

Painless resembles Java with some simplifications. Access document fields via doc['field'].value:
  "source": "return doc['price'].value * params.discount",
  "params": { "discount": 0.9 }

Using params improves performance by compiling the script once and substituting parameters at runtime.

Runtime fields

Runtime fields are computed at query time and not stored:
  PUT /my-index/_mapping
  {
    "runtime": {
      "full_name": {
        "type": "keyword",
        "script": {
          "source": "emit(doc['first'].value + ' ' + doc['last'].value)"
        }
      }
    }
  }

Runtime fields can be searched and aggregated like stored fields but are computed on the fly, adding query latency.

Script score queries

Use script_score to combine standard query relevance with a custom scoring formula:
  {
    "query": {
      "script_score": {
        "query": { "match_all": {} },
        "script": {
          "source": "cosineSimilarity(params.query_vector, 'body_vector') + 1.0",
          "params": { "query_vector": [0.1, 0.2, ...] }
        }
      }
    }
  }

This enables exact (brute-force) vector similarity search using script_score. For approximate kNN, use the knn retriever instead.

Security

Painless scripts run in a security manager sandbox. They cannot access the filesystem, network, or Elasticsearch cluster state directly. This prevents malicious scripts from compromising the node.

The Elastic Inference Service (EIS) provides hosted machine learning inference without requiring dedicated ML nodes. EIS runs model inference in Elastic's cloud infrastructure.

Availability

EIS is automatically enabled on:
- Elastic Cloud Hosted deployments
- Elastic Cloud Serverless projects
- Self-managed clusters connected to EIS via the connect-self-managed-cluster-to-eis workflow

Supported tasks

text_embedding: Dense vector embeddings for semantic search.
sparse_embedding: Sparse vector representations (ELSER-compatible).
rerank: Cross-encoder reranking for relevance improvement.
chat_completion: LLM completion for AI assistant features.

Default EIS inference endpoints

For Elastic Cloud deployments, EIS pre-configures default inference endpoints. The semantic_text field type uses the default endpoint when no inference_id is specified. Important: default endpoint assignments can change across versions and deployment types. Always specify inference_id explicitly in production mappings.

EIS vs. ML nodes

ML nodes run models locally within your Elasticsearch cluster. This gives more control over model selection and avoids network latency to EIS. EIS eliminates the need to allocate and manage ML nodes but uses Elastic's managed models.

Using EIS with semantic_text

  PUT /my-index
  {
    "mappings": {
      "properties": {
        "content": {
          "type": "semantic_text"
        }
      }
    }
  }

With no inference_id specified, EIS provides the embedding model. Search using the match query:
  POST /my-index/_search
  {
    "query": {
      "match": {
        "content": { "query": "What causes cluster health to go red?" }
      }
    }
  }

An alias is a secondary name for one or more indices. Aliases allow you to change the backing index without changing application code.

Creating aliases

  POST /_aliases
  {
    "actions": [
      { "add": { "index": "my-index-v2", "alias": "my-index" } }
    ]
  }

Write index

When an alias points to multiple indices, designate one as the write index to receive all index operations:
  POST /_aliases
  {
    "actions": [
      { "add": { "index": "my-index-v2", "alias": "my-index", "is_write_index": true } },
      { "add": { "index": "my-index-v1", "alias": "my-index", "is_write_index": false } }
    ]
  }

Filtered aliases

A filtered alias restricts search results to a subset of documents:
  POST /_aliases
  {
    "actions": [{
      "add": {
        "index": "logs",
        "alias": "logs-errors",
        "filter": { "term": { "level": "error" } }
      }
    }]
  }

Routing aliases

Use routing to control shard routing for alias operations:
  POST /_aliases
  {
    "actions": [{
      "add": {
        "index": "my-index",
        "alias": "my-alias",
        "routing": "user-123"
      }
    }]
  }

Index template aliases

Aliases can be defined in index templates so they are automatically applied when new indices matching the template pattern are created.

Aliases vs. data streams

Data streams are the modern replacement for time-series index aliases with write index patterns. Data streams automatically manage rollover without requiring manual alias management. For non-time-series data or when you need more control, index aliases remain the appropriate tool.
